<font color="#FF0000">MUSTANG TWO FOUR</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 20:53:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
What!!! Humanize a grunt?<br><br>
Four years ago I ran for Congress, I would have voted for that bill if I had won, even if I didn't know you were a vet.<br>
As &quot;Chief,&quot; used to tell us, you're all a bunch of worms, little worms.<br>
Someone forgot to tell Chief a Ute indian that it was ok to show fear among friends. He wouldn't give up his M-14 for anything. When we had our resent reunion. 12 of us who had not seen or spoken to anyone else from our unit in over 30 years got together for 3 days early this year. Three of the local papers ran stories about that event. The main paper wrote up a pretty good story about him and Izzie a Shoeshone Indian from Utah.    <br><br>
Where did the bird dogs that dropped cans of Budweiser's, wrapped in the Stars and stripes newspapers operate out of?  Every once in a while they would do that while we were out on operations, talk about a morale booster.<br><br>
I feel like I've been asleep for 30 years. <br>
It was not until I started the book that I began to do research and began to look back to try to comprehend what happened. I decided not to do that, but to write the book as it happened and what I experienced. <br><br>
After the war, I became too busy in a career, busting criminals with AK-47's in Watts and East LA. So, the war for justice never ended for me, I only changed uniforms.<br><br>
Funny I don't feel like I've been chest beating.  I have found that many, even those that served in Nam in a war zone never experienced the intensity of the firefights our unit experienced during the time of my tour of duty. It's not bragging, I just thought everyone engaged the enemy as we had. <br>
Now, doing the research that I have done I realized that, we, especially those that served in our unit downplayed our involvement and what we accomplished. <br>
I never understood why a bunch of veterans standing around jaw jacking in a VFW hall often fell silent when I shared any portion of my war experiences with them. These dialog threads have helped me realize a lot. Your poetry can truly be appreciated by those that have had to fight for life and who have fought fear itself. Thanks for the memories, they have meant a lot to me. <br><br>
 <br>

<p><code>--   (Cook Barela) </code><p>


